# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: low-noise-amplifier
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:low-noise-amplifier/friis-formulas-for-noise] Friis's formula is used to calculate the total noise factor of a cascade of stages, each with its own noise factor and power gain (assuming that the impedances are matched at each stage).
[src:low-noise-amplifier/friis-formulas-for-noise] The total noise factor can then be used to calculate the total noise figure.
[src:low-noise-amplifier/friis-formulas-for-noise] where $F_{i}$ and $G_{i}$ are the noise factor and available power gain, respectively, of the *i*-th stage, and *n* is the number of stages.
[src:low-noise-amplifier/friis-formulas-for-noise] Both magnitudes are expressed as ratios, not in decibels.
[src:low-noise-amplifier/friis-formulas-for-noise] An important consequence of this formula is that the overall noise figure of a radio receiver is primarily established by the noise figure of its first amplifying stage.
[src:low-noise-amplifier/friis-formulas-for-noise] Subsequent stages have a diminishing effect on signal-to-noise ratio.
[src:low-noise-amplifier/friis-formulas-for-noise] For this reason, the first stage amplifier in a receiver is often called the low-noise amplifier (LNA).
[src:low-noise-amplifier/friis-formulas-for-noise] where $F_{\mathrm {rest} }$ is the overall noise factor of the subsequent stages.
[src:low-noise-amplifier/friis-formulas-for-noise] According to the equation, the overall noise factor, $F_{\mathrm {receiver} }$ , is dominated by the noise factor of the LNA, $F_{\mathrm {LNA} }$ , if the gain is sufficiently high.
[src:low-noise-amplifier/friis-formulas-for-noise] For a derivation of Friis' formula for the case of three cascaded amplifiers ( $n=3$ ) consider the image below.
[src:low-noise-amplifier/friis-formulas-for-noise] A source outputs a signal of power $S_{i}$ and noise of power $N_{i}$ .
[src:low-noise-amplifier/friis-formulas-for-noise] Therefore the SNR at the input of the receiver chain is ${\text{SNR}}_{i}=S_{i}/N_{i}$ .
[src:low-noise-amplifier/friis-formulas-for-noise] The signal of power $S_{i}$ gets amplified by all three amplifiers.
[src:low-noise-amplifier/friis-formulas-for-noise] Thus the signal power at the output of the third amplifier is $S_{o}=S_{i}\cdot G_{1}G_{2}G_{3}$ .
[src:low-noise-amplifier/friis-formulas-for-noise] The total input power of the k -th amplifier in the cascade (noise and signal) is $S_{k-1}+N_{k-1}$ .
[src:low-noise-amplifier/friis-formulas-for-noise] It is amplified according to the amplifier's power gain $G_{k}$ .
[src:low-noise-amplifier/friis-formulas-for-noise] Additionally, the amplifier adds noise with power $N_{\mathrm {a} ,k}$ .
[src:low-noise-amplifier/lc-circuit] An **LC circuit**, also called a **resonant circuit**, **tank circuit**, or **tuned circuit**, is an electric circuit consisting of an inductor, represented by the letter L, and a capacitor, represented by the letter C, connected together.
[src:low-noise-amplifier/lc-circuit] The circuit can act as an electrical resonator, an electrical analogue of a tuning fork, storing energy oscillating at the circuit's resonant frequency.
[src:low-noise-amplifier/lc-circuit] LC circuits are used either for generating signals at a particular frequency, or picking out a signal at a particular frequency from a more complex signal; this function is called a bandpass filter.
[src:low-noise-amplifier/lc-circuit] They are key components in many electronic devices, particularly radio equipment, used in circuits such as oscillators, filters, tuners and frequency mixers.
[src:low-noise-amplifier/lc-circuit] An LC circuit is an idealized model since it assumes there is no dissipation of energy due to resistance.
[src:low-noise-amplifier/lc-circuit] Any practical implementation of an LC circuit will always include loss resulting from small but non-zero resistance within the components and connecting wires.
[src:low-noise-amplifier/lc-circuit] The purpose of an LC circuit is usually to oscillate with minimal damping, so the resistance is made as low as possible.
[src:low-noise-amplifier/lc-circuit] While no practical circuit is without losses, it is nonetheless instructive to study this ideal form of the circuit to gain understanding and physical intuition.
[src:low-noise-amplifier/lc-circuit] For a circuit model incorporating resistance, see RLC circuit.
[src:low-noise-amplifier/lc-circuit] The two-element LC circuit described above is the simplest type of **inductor-capacitor network** (or **LC network**).
[src:low-noise-amplifier/lc-circuit] It is also referred to as a *second order LC circuit* to distinguish it from more complicated (higher order) LC networks with more inductors and capacitors.
[src:low-noise-amplifier/lc-circuit] Such LC networks with more than two reactances may have more than one resonant frequency.
[src:low-noise-amplifier/lc-circuit] The order of the network is the order of the rational function describing the network in the complex frequency variable s.
[src:low-noise-amplifier/lc-circuit] Generally, the order is equal to the number of L and C elements in the circuit and in any event cannot exceed this number.
[src:low-noise-amplifier/lc-circuit] An LC circuit, oscillating at its natural resonant frequency, can store electrical energy.
[src:low-noise-amplifier/lc-circuit] A capacitor stores energy in the electric field (E) between its plates, depending on the voltage across it, and an inductor stores energy in its magnetic field (B), depending on the current through it.
[src:low-noise-amplifier/lc-circuit] If an inductor is connected across a charged capacitor, the voltage across the capacitor will drive a current through the inductor, building up a magnetic field around it.
[src:low-noise-amplifier/lc-circuit] The voltage across the capacitor falls to zero as the charge is used up by the current flow.
[src:low-noise-amplifier/lc-circuit] At this point, the energy stored in the coil's magnetic field induces a voltage across the coil, because inductors oppose changes in current.
[src:low-noise-amplifier/lc-circuit] This induced voltage causes a current to begin to recharge the capacitor with a voltage of opposite polarity to its original charge.
[src:low-noise-amplifier/lc-circuit] Due to Faraday's law, the EMF which drives the current is caused by a decrease in the magnetic field, thus the energy required to charge the capacitor is extracted from the magnetic field.
[src:low-noise-amplifier/lc-circuit] When the magnetic field is completely dissipated the current will stop and the charge will again be stored in the capacitor, with the opposite polarity as before.
[src:low-noise-amplifier/lc-circuit] Then the cycle will begin again, with the current flowing in the opposite direction through the inductor.
[src:low-noise-amplifier/lc-circuit] The charge flows back and forth between the plates of the capacitor, through the inductor.
[src:low-noise-amplifier/lc-circuit] The energy oscillates back and forth between the capacitor and the inductor until (if not replenished from an external circuit) internal resistance makes the oscillations die out.
[src:low-noise-amplifier/lc-circuit] The tuned circuit's action, known mathematically as a harmonic oscillator, is similar to a pendulum swinging back and forth, or water sloshing back and forth in a tank; for this reason the circuit is also called a *tank circuit*.
[src:low-noise-amplifier/lc-circuit] The natural frequency (that is, the frequency at which it will oscillate when isolated from any other system, as described above) is determined by the capacitance and inductance values.
[src:low-noise-amplifier/lc-circuit] In most applications the tuned circuit is part of a larger circuit which applies alternating current to it, driving continuous oscillations.
[src:low-noise-amplifier/lc-circuit] If the frequency of the applied current is the circuit's natural resonant frequency (natural frequency $f_{0}\,$ below), resonance will occur, and a small driving current can excite large amplitude oscillating voltages and currents.
[src:low-noise-amplifier/lc-circuit] In typical tuned circuits in electronic equipment the oscillations are very fast, from thousands to billions of times per second.
[src:low-noise-amplifier/lc-circuit] Resonance occurs when an LC circuit is driven from an external source at an angular frequency *ω*0 at which the inductive and capacitive reactances are equal in magnitude.
[src:low-noise-amplifier/lc-circuit] The frequency at which this equality holds for the particular circuit is called the resonant frequency.
[src:low-noise-amplifier/lc-circuit] where L is the inductance in henries, and C is the capacitance in farads.
[src:low-noise-amplifier/lc-circuit] The angular frequency *ω*0 has units of radians per second.
[src:low-noise-amplifier/lc-circuit] The resonance effect of the LC circuit has many important applications in signal processing and communications systems.
[src:low-noise-amplifier/lc-circuit] and can be solved for A and B by considering the initial conditions.
[src:low-noise-amplifier/lc-circuit] Since the exponential is complex, the solution represents a sinusoidal alternating current.
[src:low-noise-amplifier/lc-circuit] Since the electric current I is a physical quantity, it must be real-valued.
[src:low-noise-amplifier/lc-circuit] Next, we can use Euler's formula to obtain a real sinusoid with amplitude *I*0, angular frequency *ω*0 = ⁠1/√*LC*⁠, and phase angle $\phi$ .
[src:low-noise-amplifier/lc-circuit] In the series configuration of the LC circuit, the inductor (L) and capacitor (C) are connected in series, as shown here.
[src:low-noise-amplifier/lc-circuit] The total voltage V across the open terminals is simply the sum of the voltage across the inductor and the voltage across the capacitor.
[src:low-noise-amplifier/lc-circuit] The current I into the positive terminal of the circuit is equal to the current through both the capacitor and the inductor.
[src:low-noise-amplifier/lc-circuit] Inductive reactance $\ X_{\mathsf {L}}=\omega L\$ increases as frequency increases, while capacitive reactance $\ X_{\mathsf {C}}={\frac {1}{\ \omega C\ }}\$ decreases with increase in frequency (defined here as a positive number).
[src:low-noise-amplifier/lc-circuit] At one particular frequency, these two reactances are equal and the voltages across them are equal and opposite in sign; that frequency is called the resonant frequency *f*0 for the given circuit.
[src:low-noise-amplifier/lc-circuit] which is defined as the resonant angular frequency of the circuit.
[src:low-noise-amplifier/lc-circuit] In a series configuration, XC and XL cancel each other out.
[src:low-noise-amplifier/lc-circuit] In real, rather than idealised, components, the current is opposed, mostly by the resistance of the coil windings.
[src:low-noise-amplifier/lc-circuit] Thus, the current supplied to a series resonant circuit is maximal at resonance.
[src:low-noise-amplifier/lc-circuit] In the series configuration, resonance occurs when the complex electrical impedance of the circuit approaches zero.
[src:low-noise-amplifier/lc-circuit] First consider the impedance of the series LC circuit.
[src:low-noise-amplifier/lc-circuit] where $\,\omega _{0}L\ \,$ gives the reactance of the inductor at resonance.
[src:low-noise-amplifier/lc-circuit] The numerator implies that in the limit as *ω* → ±*ω*0 , the total impedance Z will be zero and otherwise non-zero.
[src:low-noise-amplifier/lc-circuit] Therefore the series LC circuit, when connected in series with a load, will act as a band-pass filter having zero impedance at the resonant frequency of the LC circuit.
[src:low-noise-amplifier/lc-circuit] When the inductor (L) and capacitor (C) are connected in parallel as shown here, the voltage V across the open terminals is equal to both the voltage across the inductor and the voltage across the capacitor.
[src:low-noise-amplifier/lc-circuit] When XL equals XC, the two branch currents are equal and opposite.
[src:low-noise-amplifier/lc-circuit] They cancel each other out to give minimal current in the main line (in principle, for a finite voltage V, there is zero current).
[src:low-noise-amplifier/lc-circuit] Since total current in the main line is minimal, in this state the total impedance is maximal.
[src:low-noise-amplifier/lc-circuit] There is also a larger current circulating in the loop formed by the capacitor and inductor.
[src:low-noise-amplifier/lc-circuit] For a finite voltage V, this circulating current is finite, with value given by the respective voltage-current relationships of the capacitor and inductor.
[src:low-noise-amplifier/lc-circuit] However, for a finite total current I in the main line, in principle, the circulating current would be infinite.
[src:low-noise-amplifier/lc-circuit] In reality, the circulating current in this case is limited by resistance in the circuit, particularly resistance in the inductor windings.
[src:low-noise-amplifier/lc-circuit] Any branch current is not minimal at resonance, but each is given separately by dividing source voltage (V) by reactance (Z).
[src:low-noise-amplifier/lc-circuit] Hence *I* = *⁠ V /Z⁠* , as per Ohm's law.
[src:low-noise-amplifier/lc-circuit] The same analysis may be applied to the parallel LC circuit.
[src:low-noise-amplifier/lc-circuit] but for all other values of ω the impedance is finite.
[src:low-noise-amplifier/lc-circuit] Thus, the parallel LC circuit connected in series with a load will act as band-stop filter having infinite impedance at the resonant frequency of the LC circuit, while the parallel LC circuit connected in parallel with a load will act as band-pass filter.
[src:low-noise-amplifier/lc-circuit] The LC circuit can be solved using the Laplace transform.
[src:low-noise-amplifier/lc-circuit] The Laplace transform has turned our differential equation into an algebraic equation.
[src:low-noise-amplifier/lc-circuit] Solving for V in the s domain (frequency domain) is much simpler viz.
[src:low-noise-amplifier/lc-circuit] The final term is dependent on the exact form of the input voltage.
[src:low-noise-amplifier/lc-circuit] Two common cases are the Heaviside step function and a sine wave.
[src:low-noise-amplifier/lc-circuit] where U is the amplitude and $\omega _{f}$ the frequency of the applied function.
[src:low-noise-amplifier/lc-circuit] The first evidence that a capacitor and inductor could produce electrical oscillations was discovered in 1826 by French scientist Felix Savary.
[src:low-noise-amplifier/lc-circuit] He found that when a Leyden jar was discharged through a wire wound around an iron needle, sometimes the needle was left magnetized in one direction and sometimes in the opposite direction.
[src:low-noise-amplifier/lc-circuit] He correctly deduced that this was caused by a damped oscillating discharge current in the wire, which reversed the magnetization of the needle back and forth until it was too small to have an effect, leaving the needle magnetized in a random direction.
[src:low-noise-amplifier/lc-circuit] American physicist Joseph Henry repeated Savary's experiment in 1842 and came to the same conclusion, apparently independently.
[src:low-noise-amplifier/lc-circuit] Irish scientist William Thomson (Lord Kelvin) in 1853 showed mathematically that the discharge of a Leyden jar through an inductance should be oscillatory, and derived its resonant frequency.
[src:low-noise-amplifier/lc-circuit] British radio researcher Oliver Lodge, by discharging a large battery of Leyden jars through a long wire, created a tuned circuit with its resonant frequency in the audio range, which produced a musical tone from the spark when it was discharged.
[src:low-noise-amplifier/lc-circuit] In 1857, German physicist Berend Wilhelm Feddersen photographed the spark produced by a resonant Leyden jar circuit in a rotating mirror, providing visible evidence of the oscillations.
[src:low-noise-amplifier/lc-circuit] In 1868, Scottish physicist James Clerk Maxwell calculated the effect of applying an alternating current to a circuit with inductance and capacitance, showing that the response is maximum at the resonant frequency.
[src:low-noise-amplifier/lc-circuit] The first example of an electrical resonance curve was published in 1887 by German physicist Heinrich Hertz in his pioneering paper on the discovery of radio waves, showing the length of spark obtainable from his spark-gap LC resonator detectors as a function of frequency.
[src:low-noise-amplifier/lc-circuit] One of the first demonstrations of resonance between tuned circuits was Lodge's "syntonic jars" experiment around 1889.
[src:low-noise-amplifier/lc-circuit] He placed two resonant circuits next to each other, each consisting of a Leyden jar connected to an adjustable one-turn coil with a spark gap.
[src:low-noise-amplifier/lc-circuit] When a high voltage from an induction coil was applied to one tuned circuit, creating sparks and thus oscillating currents, sparks were excited in the other tuned circuit only when the circuits were adjusted to resonance.
[src:low-noise-amplifier/lc-circuit] Lodge and some English scientists preferred the term "*syntony*" for this effect, but the term "*resonance*" eventually stuck.
[src:low-noise-amplifier/lc-circuit] The first practical use for LC circuits was in the 1890s in spark-gap radio transmitters to allow the receiver and transmitter to be tuned to the same frequency.
[src:low-noise-amplifier/lc-circuit] The first patent for a radio system that allowed tuning was filed by Lodge in 1897, although the first practical systems were invented in 1900 by Italian radio pioneer Guglielmo Marconi.
[src:low-noise-amplifier/low-noise-amplifier] A **low-noise amplifier** (**LNA**) is an electronic component that amplifies a very low-power signal without significantly degrading its signal-to-noise ratio (SNR).
[src:low-noise-amplifier/low-noise-amplifier] Any electronic amplifier will increase the power of both the signal and the noise present at its input, but the amplifier will also introduce some additional noise.
[src:low-noise-amplifier/low-noise-amplifier] LNAs are designed to minimize that additional noise, by choosing special components, operating points, and circuit topologies.
[src:low-noise-amplifier/low-noise-amplifier] Minimizing additional noise must balance with other design goals such as power gain and impedance matching.
[src:low-noise-amplifier/low-noise-amplifier] LNAs are found in radio communications systems, amateur radio stations, medical instruments and electronic test equipment.
[src:low-noise-amplifier/low-noise-amplifier] A typical LNA may supply a power gain of 100 (20 decibels (dB)) while decreasing the SNR by less than a factor of two (a 3 dB noise figure (NF)).
[src:low-noise-amplifier/low-noise-amplifier] Although LNAs are primarily concerned with weak signals that are just above the noise floor, they must also consider the presence of larger signals that cause intermodulation distortion.
[src:low-noise-amplifier/low-noise-amplifier] Antennas are a common source of weak signals.
[src:low-noise-amplifier/low-noise-amplifier] An outdoor antenna is often connected to its receiver by a transmission line called a *feed line*.
[src:low-noise-amplifier/low-noise-amplifier] Losses in the feed line lower the received signal-to-noise ratio: a feed line loss of 3 dB degrades the receiver signal-to-noise ratio (SNR) by 3 dB.
[src:low-noise-amplifier/low-noise-amplifier] An example is a feed line made from 10 feet (3.0 m) of RG-174 coaxial cable and used with a global positioning system (GPS) receiver.
[src:low-noise-amplifier/low-noise-amplifier] The loss in that feed line is 3.2 dB at 1 GHz; approximately 5 dB at the GPS frequency (1.57542 GHz).
[src:low-noise-amplifier/low-noise-amplifier] This feed line loss can be avoided by placing an LNA at the antenna, which supplies enough gain to offset the loss.
[src:low-noise-amplifier/low-noise-amplifier] An LNA is a key component at the front-end of a radio receiver circuit to help reduce unwanted noise in particular.
[src:low-noise-amplifier/low-noise-amplifier] Friis' formulas for noise models the noise in a multi-stage signal collection circuit.
[src:low-noise-amplifier/low-noise-amplifier] In most receivers, the overall NF is dominated by the first few stages of the RF front end.
[src:low-noise-amplifier/low-noise-amplifier] By using an LNA close to the signal source, the effect of noise from subsequent stages of the receive chain in the circuit is reduced by the signal gain created by the LNA, while the noise created by the LNA itself is injected directly into the received signal.
[src:low-noise-amplifier/low-noise-amplifier] The LNA boosts the desired signals' power while adding as little noise and distortion as possible.
[src:low-noise-amplifier/low-noise-amplifier] The work done by the LNA enables optimum retrieval of the desired signal in the later stages of the system.
[src:low-noise-amplifier/low-noise-amplifier] Low noise amplifiers are the building blocks of communication systems and instruments.
[src:low-noise-amplifier/low-noise-amplifier] 1 dB), enough gain to boost the signal (e.g.
[src:low-noise-amplifier/low-noise-amplifier] 10 dB) and a large enough inter-modulation and compression point (IP3 and P1dB) to do the work required of it.
[src:low-noise-amplifier/low-noise-amplifier] Further specifications are the LNA's operating bandwidth, gain flatness, stability, input and output voltage standing wave ratio (VSWR).
[src:low-noise-amplifier/low-noise-amplifier] For low noise, a high amplification is required for the amplifier in the first stage.
[src:low-noise-amplifier/low-noise-amplifier] Therefore, junction field-effect transistors (JFETs) and high-electron-mobility transistors (HEMTs) are often used.
[src:low-noise-amplifier/low-noise-amplifier] They are driven in a high-current regime, which is not energy-efficient but reduces the relative amount of shot noise.
[src:low-noise-amplifier/low-noise-amplifier] It also requires input and output impedance matching circuits for narrow-band circuits to enhance the gain (*see Gain-bandwidth product*).
[src:low-noise-amplifier/low-noise-amplifier] Amplifiers need a device to provide gain.
[src:low-noise-amplifier/low-noise-amplifier] In the 1940s, that device was a vacuum tube, but now it is usually a transistor.
[src:low-noise-amplifier/low-noise-amplifier] The transistor may be one of many varieties of bipolar transistors or field-effect transistors.
[src:low-noise-amplifier/low-noise-amplifier] Other devices producing gain, such as tunnel diodes, may be used.
[src:low-noise-amplifier/low-noise-amplifier] Broadly speaking, two categories of transistor models are used in LNA design: Small-signal models use quasi-linear models of noise and large-signal models consider non-linear mixing.
[src:low-noise-amplifier/low-noise-amplifier] The amount of gain applied is often a compromise.
[src:low-noise-amplifier/low-noise-amplifier] On the one hand, high gain makes weak signals strong.
[src:low-noise-amplifier/low-noise-amplifier] On the other hand, high gain means higher-level signals, and such high-level signals with high gain may exceed the amplifier's dynamic range or cause other types of noise such as harmonic distortion or nonlinear mixing.
[src:low-noise-amplifier/low-noise-amplifier] The noise figure helps determine the efficiency of a particular LNA.
[src:low-noise-amplifier/low-noise-amplifier] LNA suitability for a particular application is typically based on its noise figure.
[src:low-noise-amplifier/low-noise-amplifier] In general, a low noise figure results in better signal reception.
[src:low-noise-amplifier/low-noise-amplifier] The circuit topology affects input and output impedance.
[src:low-noise-amplifier/low-noise-amplifier] In general, the source impedance is matched to the input impedance because that will maximize the power transfer from the source to the device.
[src:low-noise-amplifier/low-noise-amplifier] If the source impedance is low, then a common base or common gate circuit topology may be appropriate.
[src:low-noise-amplifier/low-noise-amplifier] For a medium source impedance, a common emitter or common source topology may be used.
[src:low-noise-amplifier/low-noise-amplifier] With a high source resistance, a common collector or common drain topology may be appropriate.
[src:low-noise-amplifier/low-noise-amplifier] An input impedance match may not produce the lowest noise figure.
[src:low-noise-amplifier/low-noise-amplifier] Another design issue is the noise introduced by biasing networks.
[src:low-noise-amplifier/low-noise-amplifier] In communication circuits, biasing networks play a critical role in establishing stable operating points for active components, but they also introduce noise.
[src:low-noise-amplifier/low-noise-amplifier] The primary types of noise introduced by these networks are thermal noise and flicker noise.
[src:low-noise-amplifier/low-noise-amplifier] Thermal noise arises from resistive elements in the network, which is inevitable as any resistive component generates noise due to the random motion of charge carriers.
[src:low-noise-amplifier/low-noise-amplifier] This type of noise is especially problematic at high frequencies.
[src:low-noise-amplifier/low-noise-amplifier] Flicker noise, also known as 1/f noise, is related to the current flow through devices like transistors and becomes more significant at lower frequencies.
[src:low-noise-amplifier/low-noise-amplifier] In an LNA, the biasing network must be carefully designed to minimize the impact of noise on the overall performance.
[src:low-noise-amplifier/low-noise-amplifier] Improper biasing can lead to increased noise figures, compromising the signal-to-noise ratio and degrading communication system performance.
[src:low-noise-amplifier/low-noise-amplifier] The design and selection of components within the bias network are therefore crucial to ensuring low-noise operation, particularly in systems that rely on amplifying weak signals.
[src:low-noise-amplifier/low-noise-amplifier] In practice, the bias point strongly affects an LNA’s noise figure, gain, linearity, and stability.
[src:low-noise-amplifier/low-noise-amplifier] A transistor’s key noise parameters, the minimum noise factor (F_min), the equivalent noise resistance (R_n), and the optimum source match (Γ_opt), all change with current and voltage.
[src:low-noise-amplifier/low-noise-amplifier] Designers therefore sweep the quiescent current and voltage and pick a bias that meets the noise figure target while leaving headroom for linear operation, rather than simply using the highest current available.
[src:low-noise-amplifier/low-noise-amplifier] Common bias schemes include simple self bias, which uses a source or emitter resistor with a gate or base divider, and active bias loops that hold the quiescent current over temperature and process variation.
[src:low-noise-amplifier/low-noise-amplifier] Self bias is passive and tends to stabilize with temperature but slightly reduces available gain.
[src:low-noise-amplifier/low-noise-amplifier] Active bias improves repeatability, at the cost of extra circuitry and possible loop stability checks.
[src:low-noise-amplifier/low-noise-amplifier] Technology specific sequencing also matters.
[src:low-noise-amplifier/low-noise-amplifier] Many depletion mode LNAs need a negative gate bias and a positive drain supply.
[src:low-noise-amplifier/low-noise-amplifier] To prevent overcurrent during power up and power down, the gate bias is applied and removed before the drain supply.
[src:low-noise-amplifier/low-noise-amplifier] Designers often use bias controllers or simple sequencing circuits, sometimes with temperature compensation.
[src:low-noise-amplifier/low-noise-amplifier] By contrast, some LNAs, such as CMOS, usually run from a single positive supply and set current with emitter or source degeneration plus active bias.
[src:low-noise-amplifier/low-noise-amplifier] Because S parameters and stability factors change with bias and temperature, LNAs that may see arbitrary source impedances are typically checked for unconditional stability across bias and temperature corners.
[src:low-noise-amplifier/low-noise-amplifier] Only the minimum damping or feedback needed is added so that stability does not unduly raise the noise figure.
[src:low-noise-amplifier/low-noise-amplifier] LNAs are used in communications receivers such as in radio telescopes, cellular telephones, GPS receivers, wireless LANs (WiFi), and satellite communications.
[src:low-noise-amplifier/low-noise-amplifier] In a satellite communications system, the ground station receiving antenna uses an LNA because the received signal is weak since satellites have limited power and therefore use low-power transmitters.
[src:low-noise-amplifier/low-noise-amplifier] The satellites are also distant and suffer path loss: low Earth orbit satellites might be 120 miles (190 km) away; a geosynchronous satellite is 22,236 miles (35,785 km) away.
[src:low-noise-amplifier/low-noise-amplifier] The LNA boosts the antenna signal to overcome feed line losses between the antenna and the receiver.
[src:low-noise-amplifier/low-noise-amplifier] LNAs can enhance the performance of software-defined radio (SDR) receiver systems.
[src:low-noise-amplifier/low-noise-amplifier] SDRs are typically designed to be general purpose and therefore the noise figure is not optimized for any one particular application.
[src:low-noise-amplifier/low-noise-amplifier] With an LNA and appropriate filter, performance is improved over a range of frequencies.
[src:low-noise-amplifier/noise-figure] The noise factor is defined as the unitless ratio of the output noise power of a device to the portion thereof attributable to thermal noise in the input termination at standard noise temperature *T*0 (usually 290 K).
[src:low-noise-amplifier/noise-figure] The noise factor is thus the ratio of actual output noise to that which would remain if the device itself did not introduce noise, which is equivalent to the ratio of input SNR to output SNR.
[src:low-noise-amplifier/noise-figure] The noise figure is the power level of the noise factor, calculated in terms of the logarithm of noise factor and expressed in scale of decibels (dB).
[src:low-noise-amplifier/noise-figure] The noise figure is the difference in decibel (dB) between the noise output of the actual receiver to the noise output of an "ideal" receiver with the same overall gain and bandwidth when the receivers are connected to matched sources at the standard noise temperature *T*0 (usually 290 K).
[src:low-noise-amplifier/noise-figure] The noise power from a simple load is equal to *kTB*, where *k* is the Boltzmann constant, *T* is the absolute temperature of the load (for example a resistor), and *B* is the measurement bandwidth.
[src:low-noise-amplifier/noise-figure] This makes the noise figure a useful figure of merit for terrestrial systems, where the antenna effective temperature is usually near the standard 290 K.
[src:low-noise-amplifier/noise-figure] In this case, one receiver with a noise figure, say 2 dB better than another, will have an output signal-to-noise ratio that is about 2 dB better than the other.
[src:low-noise-amplifier/noise-figure] However, in the case of satellite communications systems, where the receiver antenna is pointed out into cold space, the antenna effective temperature is often colder than 290 K.
[src:low-noise-amplifier/noise-figure] In these cases a 2 dB improvement in receiver noise figure will result in more than a 2 dB improvement in the output signal-to-noise ratio.
[src:low-noise-amplifier/noise-figure] For this reason, the related figure of *effective noise temperature* is therefore often used instead of the noise figure for characterizing satellite-communication receivers and low-noise amplifiers.
[src:low-noise-amplifier/noise-figure] where SNRi and SNRo are the input and output signal-to-noise ratios respectively.
[src:low-noise-amplifier/noise-figure] The SNR quantities are unitless power ratios.
[src:low-noise-amplifier/noise-figure] Note that this specific definition is only valid for an input signal of which the noise is *Ni=kT0B*.
[src:low-noise-amplifier/noise-figure] where SNRi, dB and SNRo, dB are in units of (dB).
[src:low-noise-amplifier/noise-figure] These formulae are only valid when the input termination is at standard noise temperature *T*0 = 290 K, although in practice small differences in temperature do not significantly affect the values.
[src:low-noise-amplifier/noise-figure] Attenuators have a noise factor *F* equal to their attenuation ratio *L* when their physical temperature equals *T*0.
[src:low-noise-amplifier/noise-figure] where *F**n* is the noise factor for the *n*-th device, and *G**n* is the power gain (linear, not in dB) of the *n*-th device.
[src:low-noise-amplifier/noise-figure] The first amplifier in a chain usually has the most significant effect on the total noise figure because the noise figures of the following stages are reduced by stage gains.
[src:low-noise-amplifier/noise-figure] Consequently, the first amplifier usually has a low noise figure, and the noise figure requirements of subsequent stages is usually more relaxed.
[src:low-noise-amplifier/noise-figure] The noise factor may be expressed as a function of the additional output referred noise power $N_{a}$ and the power gain G of an amplifier.
[src:low-noise-amplifier/noise-figure] and assuming a system which has a noisy single stage amplifier.
[src:low-noise-amplifier/noise-figure] In cascaded systems $N_{i}$ does not refer to the output noise of the previous component.
[src:low-noise-amplifier/noise-figure] An input termination at the standard noise temperature is still assumed for the individual component.
[src:low-noise-amplifier/noise-figure] This means that the additional noise power added by each component is independent of the other components.
[src:low-noise-amplifier/noise-figure] The above describes noise in electrical systems.
[src:low-noise-amplifier/noise-figure] The optical noise figure is discussed in multiple sources.
[src:low-noise-amplifier/noise-figure] Electric sources generate noise with a power spectral density, or energy per mode, equal to *kT*, where *k* is the Boltzmann constant and *T* is the absolute temperature.
[src:low-noise-amplifier/noise-figure] One mode has two quadratures, i.e. the amplitudes of cos $\mathrm {\omega } t$ and sin $\mathrm {\omega } t$ oscillations of voltages, currents or fields.
[src:low-noise-amplifier/noise-figure] However, there is also noise in optical systems.
[src:low-noise-amplifier/noise-figure] In these, the sources have no fundamental noise.
[src:low-noise-amplifier/noise-figure] Instead the energy quantization causes notable shot noise in the detector.
[src:low-noise-amplifier/noise-figure] In an optical receiver which can output one available mode or two available quadratures this corresponds to a noise power spectral density, or energy per mode, of *hf* where *h* is the Planck constant and *f* is the optical frequency.
[src:low-noise-amplifier/noise-figure] In an optical receiver with only one available quadrature the shot noise has a power spectral density, or energy per mode, of only *hf*/2.
[src:low-noise-amplifier/noise-figure] In the 1990s, an optical noise figure has been defined.
[src:low-noise-amplifier/noise-figure] This has been called *F**pnf* for *p*hoton *n*umber *f*luctuations.
[src:low-noise-amplifier/noise-figure] The powers needed for SNR and noise factor calculation are the electrical powers caused by the current in a photodiode.
[src:low-noise-amplifier/noise-figure] SNR is the square of mean photocurrent divided by variance of photocurrent.
[src:low-noise-amplifier/noise-figure] Monochromatic or sufficiently attenuated light has a Poisson distribution of detected photons.
[src:low-noise-amplifier/noise-figure] If, during a detection interval the expectation value of detected photons is *n* then the variance is also *n* and one obtains *SNR**pnf,in* = *n*2/*n* = *n*.
[src:low-noise-amplifier/noise-figure] Behind an optical amplifier with power gain *G* there will be a mean of *Gn* detectable signal photons.
[src:low-noise-amplifier/noise-figure] In the limit of large *n* the variance of photons is *Gn*(2*n**sp*(*G*-1)+1) where *n**sp* is the spontaneous emission factor.
[src:low-noise-amplifier/noise-figure] Photocurrent *I* is proportional to optical power *P*.
[src:low-noise-amplifier/noise-figure] *P* is proportional to squares of a field amplitude (electric or magnetic).
[src:low-noise-amplifier/noise-figure] So, the receiver is nonlinear in amplitude.
[src:low-noise-amplifier/noise-figure] The "Power" needed for *SNR**pnf* calculation is proportional to the 4th power of the signal amplitude.
[src:low-noise-amplifier/noise-figure] But for *F**e* in the electrical domain the power is proportional to the square of the signal amplitude.
[src:low-noise-amplifier/noise-figure] If *SNR**pnf* is a noise factor then its definition must be independent of measurement apparatus and frequency.
[src:low-noise-amplifier/noise-figure] Consider the signal "Power" in the sense of *SNR**pnf* definition.
[src:low-noise-amplifier/noise-figure] Behind an amplifier it is proportional to *G*2*n*2.
[src:low-noise-amplifier/noise-figure] We may replace the photodiode by a thermal power meter, and measured photocurrent *I* by measured temperature change $\mathrm {\Delta \theta }$ .
[src:low-noise-amplifier/noise-figure] "Power", being proportional to *I*2 or *P*2, is also proportional to $(\mathrm {\Delta \theta } )$ 2.
[src:low-noise-amplifier/noise-figure] Thermal power meters can be built at all frequencies.
[src:low-noise-amplifier/noise-figure] Hence it is possible to lower the frequency from optical (say 200 THz) to electrical (say 200 MHz).
[src:low-noise-amplifier/noise-figure] Still there, "Power" must be proportional to $(\mathrm {\Delta \theta } )$ 2 or *P*2.
[src:low-noise-amplifier/noise-figure] Electrical power *P* is proportional to the square *U*2 of voltage *U*.
[src:low-noise-amplifier/noise-figure] These implications are in obvious conflict with ~150 years of physics.
[src:low-noise-amplifier/noise-figure] They are compelling consequence of calling *F**pnf* a noise factor, or noise figure when expressed in dB.
[src:low-noise-amplifier/noise-figure] At any given electrical frequency, noise occurs in both quadratures, i.e. in phase (I) and in quadrature (Q) with the signal.
[src:low-noise-amplifier/noise-figure] Both these quadratures are available behind the electrical amplifier.
[src:low-noise-amplifier/noise-figure] But the direct detection photoreceiver needed for measurement of *SNR**pnf* takes mainly the in-phase noise into account whereas quadrature noise can be neglected for high *n*.
[src:low-noise-amplifier/noise-figure] Also, the receiver outputs only one baseband signal, corresponding to quadrature.
[src:low-noise-amplifier/noise-figure] So, one quadrature or degree-of-freedom is lost.
[src:low-noise-amplifier/noise-figure] For an optical amplifier with large *G* it holds *F**pnf* ≥ 2 whereas for an *e*lectrical amplifier it holds *F**e* ≥ 1.
[src:low-noise-amplifier/noise-figure] Moreover, today's long-haul optical fiber communication is dominated by coherent optical I&Q receivers but *F**pnf* does not describe the SNR degradation observed in these.
[src:low-noise-amplifier/noise-figure] Another optical noise figure *F**ase* for *a*mplified *s*pontaneous *e*mission has been defined.
[src:low-noise-amplifier/noise-figure] But the noise factor *F**ase* is not the SNR degradation factor in any optical receiver.
[src:low-noise-amplifier/noise-figure] All the above conflicts are resolved by the optical in-phase and quadrature noise factor and figure *F**o,IQ*.
[src:low-noise-amplifier/noise-figure] It can be measured using a coherent optical I&Q receiver.
[src:low-noise-amplifier/noise-figure] In these, power of the output signal is proportional to the square of an optical field amplitude because they are linear in amplitude.
[src:low-noise-amplifier/noise-figure] Quantity *n**sp*(1-1/*G*) is the input-referred number of added noise photons per mode.
[src:low-noise-amplifier/noise-temperature] In electronics, **noise temperature** is one way of expressing the level of available noise power introduced by a component or source.
[src:low-noise-amplifier/noise-temperature] Thus the noise temperature is proportional to the power spectral density of the noise, $P_{\text{N}}/B$ .
[src:low-noise-amplifier/noise-temperature] That is the power that would be absorbed from the component or source by a matched load.
[src:low-noise-amplifier/noise-temperature] Noise temperature is generally a function of frequency, unlike that of an ideal resistor which is simply equal to the actual temperature of the resistor at all frequencies.
[src:low-noise-amplifier/noise-temperature] A noisy component may be modelled as a noiseless component in series with a noisy voltage source producing a voltage of *v*n, or as a noiseless component in parallel with a noisy current source producing a current of *i*n.
[src:low-noise-amplifier/noise-temperature] where R is the resistive part of the component's impedance or G is the conductance (real part) of the component's admittance.
[src:low-noise-amplifier/noise-temperature] Speaking of noise temperature therefore offers a fair comparison between components having different impedances rather than specifying the noise voltage and qualifying that number by mentioning the component's resistance.
[src:low-noise-amplifier/noise-temperature] It is also more accessible than speaking of the noise's power spectral density (in watts per hertz) since it is expressed as an ordinary temperature which can be compared to the noise level of an ideal resistor at room temperature (290 K).
[src:low-noise-amplifier/noise-temperature] Note that one can only speak of the noise temperature of a component or source whose impedance has a substantial (and measurable) resistive component.
[src:low-noise-amplifier/noise-temperature] Thus it does not make sense to talk about the noise temperature of a capacitor or of a voltage source.
[src:low-noise-amplifier/noise-temperature] The noise temperature of an amplifier refers to the noise that would be added at the amplifier's *input* (relative to the input impedance of the amplifier) in order to account for the added noise observed following amplification.
[src:low-noise-amplifier/noise-temperature] An RF receiver system is typically made up of an antenna and a receiver, and the transmission line(s) that connect the two together.
[src:low-noise-amplifier/noise-temperature] Each of these is a source of additive noise.
[src:low-noise-amplifier/noise-temperature] The additive noise in a receiving system can be of thermal origin (thermal noise) or can be from other external or internal noise-generating processes.
[src:low-noise-amplifier/noise-temperature] The contributions of all noise sources are typically lumped together and regarded as a level of thermal noise.
[src:low-noise-amplifier/noise-temperature] In an RF receiver, the overall system noise temperature $T_{S}$ equals the sum of the effective noise temperature of the receiver and transmission lines and that of the antenna.
[src:low-noise-amplifier/noise-temperature] The antenna noise temperature $T_{A}$ gives the noise power seen at the output of the antenna.
[src:low-noise-amplifier/noise-temperature] The composite noise temperature of the receiver and transmission line losses $T_{E}$ represents the noise contribution of the rest of the receiver system.
[src:low-noise-amplifier/noise-temperature] It is calculated as the effective noise that would be present at the antenna input terminals if the receiver system were perfect and created no noise.
[src:low-noise-amplifier/noise-temperature] In other words, it is a cascaded system of amplifiers and losses where the internal noise temperatures are referred to the antenna input terminals.
[src:low-noise-amplifier/noise-temperature] Thus, the summation of these two noise temperatures represents the noise input to a "perfect" receiver system.
[src:low-noise-amplifier/noise-temperature] One use of noise temperature is in the definition of a system's noise factor or noise figure.
[src:low-noise-amplifier/noise-temperature] The noise factor specifies the increase in noise power (referred to the input of an amplifier) due to a component or system when its input noise temperature is $T_{0}$ .
[src:low-noise-amplifier/noise-temperature] $T_{0}$ is customarily taken to be room temperature, 290 K.
[src:low-noise-amplifier/noise-temperature] The noise figure can also be seen as the decrease in signal-to-noise ratio (SNR) caused by passing a signal through a system if the original signal had a noise temperature of 290 K.
[src:low-noise-amplifier/noise-temperature] This is a common way of expressing the noise contributed by a radio frequency amplifier regardless of the amplifier's gain.
[src:low-noise-amplifier/noise-temperature] For instance, assume an amplifier has a noise temperature 870 K and thus a noise figure of 6 dB.
[src:low-noise-amplifier/noise-temperature] If that amplifier is used to amplify a source having a noise temperature of about room temperature (290 K), as many sources do, then the insertion of that amplifier would reduce the SNR of a signal by 6 dB.
[src:low-noise-amplifier/noise-temperature] This simple relationship is frequently applicable where the source's noise is of thermal origin since a passive transducer will often have a noise temperature similar to 290 K.
[src:low-noise-amplifier/noise-temperature] However, in many cases the input source's noise temperature is much higher, such as an antenna at lower frequencies where atmospheric noise dominates.
[src:low-noise-amplifier/noise-temperature] Then there will be little degradation of the SNR.
[src:low-noise-amplifier/noise-temperature] On the other hand, a good satellite dish looking through the atmosphere into space (so that it sees a much lower noise temperature) would have the SNR of a signal degraded by *more* than 6 dB.
[src:low-noise-amplifier/noise-temperature] In those cases a reference to the amplifier's noise temperature itself, rather than the noise figure defined according to room temperature, is more appropriate.
[src:low-noise-amplifier/noise-temperature] The noise temperature of an amplifier is commonly measured using the Y-factor method.
[src:low-noise-amplifier/noise-temperature] Therefore, the amplifier chain can be modelled as a black box having a gain of $G_{1}\cdot G_{2}\cdot G_{3}\cdots$ and a noise figure given by $NF=10\log _{10}(1+T_{\text{E}}/290)$ .
[src:low-noise-amplifier/noise-temperature] In the usual case where the gains of the amplifier's stages are much greater than one, then it can be seen that the noise temperatures of the earlier stages have a much greater influence on the resulting noise temperature than those later in the chain.
[src:low-noise-amplifier/noise-temperature] One can appreciate that the noise introduced by the first stage, for instance, is amplified by all of the stages whereas the noise introduced by later stages undergoes lesser amplification.
[src:low-noise-amplifier/noise-temperature] Another way of looking at it is that the signal applied to a later stage already has a high noise level, due to amplification of noise by the previous stages, so that the noise contribution of that stage to that already amplified signal is of less significance.
[src:low-noise-amplifier/noise-temperature] This explains why the quality of a preamplifier or RF amplifier is of particular importance in an amplifier chain.
[src:low-noise-amplifier/noise-temperature] In most cases only the noise figure of the first stage need be considered.
[src:low-noise-amplifier/noise-temperature] However one must check that the noise figure of the second stage is not so high (or that the gain of the first stage is so low) that there is SNR degradation due to the second stage anyway.
[src:low-noise-amplifier/noise-temperature] That will be a concern if the noise figure of the first stage plus that stage's gain (in decibels) is not much greater than the noise figure of the second stage.
[src:low-noise-amplifier/noise-temperature] One corollary of the Friis equation is that an attenuator prior to the first amplifier will degrade the noise figure due to the amplifier.
[src:low-noise-amplifier/noise-temperature] Effectively the noise temperature of the amplifier $T_{2}$ has been quadrupled, in addition to the (smaller) contribution due to the attenuator itself $T_{1}$ (usually room temperature if the attenuator is composed of resistors).
[src:low-noise-amplifier/noise-temperature] An antenna with poor efficiency is an example of this principle, where $G_{1}$ would represent the antenna's efficiency.
